        <p>Cannabis has been part of human culture for thousands of years — used for relaxation, creative focus, social connection, and in some contexts, therapeutic support. As attitudes and legislation evolve, more South African adults are choosing to incorporate cannabis thoughtfully into their lifestyle. Here's what a wellness-informed approach looks like.</p>

        <h2>Start with Intention</h2>
        <p>Wellness-oriented cannabis use begins with knowing why you're using it. Whether it's to unwind after a long day, improve sleep quality, ease muscle tension, or simply enjoy a social moment, having clarity of intention helps you use cannabis more mindfully and get more from the experience.</p>
        <p>Cannabis affects each person differently, depending on factors like body weight, metabolism, experience level, and the product used. What works for a friend may not work the same way for you — and that's normal.</p>

        <h2>Choosing the Right Products</h2>
        <p>The accessories and products you choose play a meaningful role in your experience. At Mount Kush, we carry a curated range of premium smoking accessories — all selected with quality and the informed consumer in mind.</p>

        <h2>Dosing: Less Is Often More</h2>
        <p>One of the most common mistakes — especially among newer or returning users — is using too much too quickly. Cannabis tolerance varies significantly between individuals, and the wellness principle of "start low, go slow" is genuinely sound advice.</p>
        <p>Give your body time to respond before reaching for more. Overconsumption can lead to anxiety, discomfort, or an experience that's the opposite of what you were hoping for.</p>

        <h2>Cannabis and Sleep</h2>
        <p>Many adults report using cannabis to support sleep, particularly where stress or an overactive mind makes it difficult to wind down. While individual responses vary, some users find that certain cannabis products — used moderately — help ease the transition into rest. That said, regular heavy use before sleep may affect sleep quality over time. Moderation and consistency matter.</p>

        <h2>Cannabis and Older Adults</h2>
        <p>An increasing number of older South African adults are exploring cannabis — often for the first time, or returning after years away. If you're in this group, a few extra considerations apply:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Cannabis can interact with certain medications. Always consult your doctor if you are on chronic medication.</li>
          <li>Start with very small amounts and be patient — effects may take longer to be felt depending on the method used.</li>
          <li>Avoid combining cannabis with alcohol, particularly if you are new to it or have not used it in a long time.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>A Note on Mental Health</h2>
        <p>Cannabis is not suitable for everyone. If you have a personal or family history of psychosis, schizophrenia, or severe anxiety, it is important to consult a healthcare professional before using cannabis. The relationship between cannabis and mental health is nuanced, and your wellbeing matters most.</p>

        <h2>Wellness Means Being Informed</h2>
        <p>The most important thing you can do is stay informed. Know what you're using, know where it comes from, understand the legal context, and use it in a way that genuinely supports your quality of life. That's what High on Healing means to us.</p>

